we had some fantastic conversations too

00:49:14.400 --> 00:49:19.400
at least in which I was taught awed

00:49:20.030 --> 00:49:23.750
by his belief

00:49:23.750 --> 00:49:27.193
in the power of science and education.

00:49:28.280 --> 00:49:29.793
And he's written papers on the subject.

00:49:29.793 --> 00:49:32.800
It's not something you have
to tell him, he knows it.

00:49:32.800 --> 00:49:36.810
The big problem now we
have is is the complexities

00:49:36.810 --> 00:49:38.400
of our present.

00:49:38.400 --> 00:49:43.400
That's why I started out with
the economy and environment.

00:49:44.850 --> 00:49:48.460
So many problems are
piling up in Washington

00:49:48.460 --> 00:49:51.797
and yet every one of these
problems has a science

00:49:51.797 --> 00:49:53.780
and education aspect to it.

00:49:53.780 --> 00:49:58.780
So we shouldn't be too fearful

00:49:59.830 --> 00:50:03.510
to push education and science

00:50:03.510 --> 00:50:07.650
as hard as we can because
that's the right key

00:50:07.650 --> 00:50:09.070
in all of these issues.

00:50:09.070 --> 00:50:10.870
You know, how do we fix global warming?

00:50:10.870 --> 00:50:13.420
Well you know that it's science

00:50:13.420 --> 00:50:15.540
and all of these other things are science.

00:50:15.540 --> 00:50:18.070
So I think we have to be emboldened

00:50:18.070 --> 00:50:21.250
to say this is the right venue

00:50:23.670 --> 00:50:28.670
for helping in the present,
under present circumstances.

00:50:31.040 --> 00:50:31.943
Gotta work at it.

00:50:34.700 --> 00:50:38.440
- [Man] Hi so you mentioned
engineering in Boston

00:50:38.440 --> 00:50:40.840
and I actually was working
at the Museum of Science

00:50:40.840 --> 00:50:43.250
on the high school approach to engineering

00:50:43.250 --> 00:50:44.083
for ninth graders.

00:50:44.083 --> 00:50:46.900
So we were sort of your
competitor in some ways

00:50:46.900 --> 00:50:50.490
to Physics First trying to do
sort of an engineering first

00:50:50.490 --> 00:50:53.430
and as we started down the
curriculum development road,

00:50:53.430 --> 00:50:56.390
we were sort of trying to
mesh with you guys and say,

00:50:56.390 --> 00:50:57.730
well let's try and get kids

00:50:57.730 --> 00:50:59.770
to understand atoms and molecules.

00:50:59.770 --> 00:51:00.900
That's a good goal.

00:51:00.900 --> 00:51:04.520
But as we got into it and we
started doing more research,

00:51:04.520 --> 00:51:06.570
we sort of came to a more

00:51:06.570 --> 00:51:10.210
of a macroscopic
thermodynamics approach right,

00:51:10.210 --> 00:51:12.510
so flow models which are
bigger in engineering

00:51:12.510 --> 00:51:15.550
than a traditional atomic
molecular interpretation,

00:51:15.550 --> 00:51:17.340
the kinetic molecular theory.

00:51:17.340 --> 00:51:20.550
And one of the things that we found

00:51:20.550 --> 00:51:22.960
that is not well addressed by physics

00:51:22.960 --> 00:51:26.070
whether in ninth grade
or you know later is

00:51:26.070 --> 00:51:28.140
and it sounds esoteric is entropy

00:51:28.140 --> 00:51:30.150
or the general running down of things.

00:51:30.150 --> 00:51:33.650
And we talked about heat but
heat as a form of energy.

00:51:33.650 --> 00:51:36.320
So I guess I have two questions.

00:51:36.320 --> 00:51:39.630
One as you move physics to be first

00:51:39.630 --> 00:51:41.630
and have this idea of let's teach it

00:51:41.630 --> 00:51:43.440
so that kids can take chemistry

00:51:43.440 --> 00:51:45.728
and focus on the atom.

00:51:45.728 --> 00:51:50.110
Have you sort of not focused
on reformulating things enough

00:51:50.110 --> 00:51:53.880
to have a better understanding
of thermodynamics

00:51:53.880 --> 00:51:56.500
as a foundation for the other subjects

00:51:56.500 --> 00:51:59.068
and I don't remember the second question.

00:51:59.068 --> 00:52:00.810
(audience laughing)

00:52:00.810 --> 00:52:01.643
- I agree.

00:52:02.500 --> 00:52:03.850
I don't have any comment on that.

00:52:03.850 --> 00:52:07.700
I think you have a, I'd have
to look in great detail,

00:52:07.700 --> 00:52:11.010
you're making very positive suggestions

00:52:11.010 --> 00:52:14.650
and I'm sure that somewhere in this,

00:52:14.650 --> 00:52:19.650
I mean there's a email
clutch of 30 or 40 teachers

00:52:21.550 --> 00:52:25.120
that communicate regularly with ideas

00:52:25.120 --> 00:52:29.100
like how to fix it better and so on.

00:52:29.100 --> 00:52:31.000
Your statement is a good one.

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:34.760
If you write it up in a little
more detail I'll circulate it

00:52:34.760 --> 00:52:37.990
among this crowd and maybe
something good will come out

00:52:37.990 --> 00:52:40.150
of the, you know, and specifically out

00:52:40.150 --> 00:52:43.773
of the re-formulation of curriculum.

00:52:44.780 --> 00:52:47.323
What you make it sounds plausible to me.

00:52:48.397 --> 00:52:49.850
- [Man] In this new
reformulations you talk a lot

00:52:49.850 --> 00:52:51.270
about commissions and I hear now

00:52:51.270 --> 00:52:52.633
that the Governors Association is planning

00:52:52.633 --> 00:52:57.633
to get together and rewrite
basically science standards

00:52:58.530 --> 00:52:59.760
and it's a question

00:52:59.760 --> 00:53:01.830
as to how much they're gonna involve AAAS

00:53:01.830 --> 00:53:03.860
and their benchmarks et cetera, et cetera.

00:53:03.860 --> 00:53:08.330
But ideas change very
slowly and difficultly,

00:53:08.330 --> 00:53:10.630
if that's a word, in this field

00:53:10.630 --> 00:53:13.650
and so how do you see that happening?

00:53:13.650 --> 00:53:14.720
How do you see new ideas

00:53:14.720 --> 00:53:17.600
and really fundamental
reformulations happening

00:53:17.600 --> 00:53:19.100
and are you optimistic about that?

00:53:19.100 --> 00:53:22.070
- Yeah, well, of course
you're always optimistic

00:53:22.070 --> 00:53:23.820
otherwise you don't do anything.

00:53:23.820 --> 00:53:28.420
But what you're touching
on is in fact the proposal

00:53:28.420 --> 00:53:31.400
that Shirley Malcolm and I tried to sell

00:53:34.500 --> 00:53:37.030
in this National Commission idea

00:53:37.030 --> 00:53:40.600
that we do need, you know,

00:53:40.600 --> 00:53:45.600
during Sputnik we didn't
have the kinds of things

00:53:46.690 --> 00:53:51.690
that were needed to combat
the menace of Soviet progress.

00:53:53.910 --> 00:53:58.910
So Eisenhower created NASA and so on.

00:53:59.380 --> 00:54:03.900
Right now we don't have a
mechanism for implementing

00:54:03.900 --> 00:54:07.847
and for smoothing the fact

00:54:08.930 --> 00:54:11.570
that we have 50 states

00:54:11.570 --> 00:54:15.420
and each you know 50 governors
and the states are beginning

00:54:15.420 --> 00:54:18.543
to do things in the way,
which is interesting,

00:54:19.667 --> 00:54:23.530
they're I think they're
called P-20 commissions

00:54:25.600 --> 00:54:30.600
and they if in fact as the
examples I've seen are correct,

00:54:32.800 --> 00:54:35.770
more and more businessmen
get involved in this.

00:54:35.770 --> 00:54:37.700
Business men getting involved

00:54:37.700 --> 00:54:42.550
in the state manipulations is positive

00:54:42.550 --> 00:54:45.050
because they're around
longer than the governors

00:54:45.050 --> 00:54:46.860
and we've got to get a mechanism

00:54:46.860 --> 00:54:49.190
whereby states can talk to each other.

00:54:49.190 --> 00:54:54.190
So that a New Jersey teacher
moving to Missouri doesn't have

00:54:54.230 --> 00:54:56.340
to learn a new language.

00:54:56.340 --> 00:54:58.010
So that there's a lot we have

00:54:58.010 --> 00:55:00.930
to do in the way of the whole system

00:55:00.930 --> 00:55:04.670
that I'm you know I waved,
we've got to improve the system

00:55:04.670 --> 00:55:05.890
and make it more coherent.

00:55:05.890 --> 00:55:08.210
We can't give up local control,

00:55:08.210 --> 00:55:11.000
that politically is out
of the question in my view

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:14.770
but we can have a strategy,

00:55:14.770 --> 00:55:17.410
a national strategy for standards,

00:55:17.410 --> 00:55:20.060
a national strategy for many things

00:55:20.060 --> 00:55:23.100
that go into the whole educational mix.

00:55:23.100 --> 00:55:24.940
That's what we need to do

00:55:24.940 --> 00:55:28.860
and that's part of the
kind of question you asked

00:55:28.860 --> 00:55:30.010
that we need an order,

00:55:30.010 --> 00:55:32.050
we need to reorganize

00:55:32.050 --> 00:55:35.993
this chaotic incoherent system we have.

00:55:40.301 --> 00:55:42.280
- [Man] Many students in high school,

00:55:42.280 --> 00:55:44.320
including those at Cal right now,

00:55:44.320 --> 00:55:46.900
did not take physics last.

00:55:46.900 --> 00:55:49.690
They didn't take it second
and they didn't take it first.

00:55:49.690 --> 00:55:52.350
They just never took physics.

00:55:52.350 --> 00:55:57.210
Is it your hope that if
physics is put first,

00:55:57.210 --> 00:55:59.260
more students will take it?

00:55:59.260 --> 00:56:00.470
Because that we have a big problem

00:56:00.470 --> 00:56:02.210
that people just don't
take science period.

00:56:02.210 --> 00:56:03.900
They're not required to take it.

00:56:03.900 --> 00:56:05.160
They'll take some.

00:56:05.160 --> 00:56:08.340
Maybe they were required
to take one science class

00:56:08.340 --> 00:56:12.000
but for the most part in my class

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:14.970
which is the the physics for non-majors

00:56:14.970 --> 00:56:17.420
about half the students
have never taken physics.

00:56:18.410 --> 00:56:20.920
That's a separate problem from
what order we have them in.

00:56:20.920 --> 00:56:22.630
What are your comments on that?

00:56:22.630 --> 00:56:25.873
- Well when the city of
San Diego, some time ago,

00:56:26.880 --> 00:56:29.890
decided to adopt Physics First

00:56:29.890 --> 00:56:34.773
and 9,000 students registered
for physics in ninth grade,

00:56:35.700 --> 00:56:37.580
this was five years ago or so,

00:56:37.580 --> 00:56:40.290
they went through a huge effort to train,

00:56:40.290 --> 00:56:41.650
a big problem is training,

00:56:41.650 --> 00:56:43.390
they're not enough physics teachers.

00:56:43.390 --> 00:56:47.210
They had to train
physical science teachers

00:56:47.210 --> 00:56:51.400
and the biology teachers to pitch in.

00:56:51.400 --> 00:56:54.200
But somehow they manage this

00:56:54.200 --> 00:56:59.200
and it went on for three
or four years successfully.

00:56:59.430 --> 00:57:00.880
They were really getting it now.

00:57:00.880 --> 00:57:03.730
The teachers are getting
more enthusiastic about it.

00:57:03.730 --> 00:57:06.460
A lot of it has to do
with not forcing teachers

00:57:06.460 --> 00:57:11.460
but having teachers being
part of this revolution

00:57:11.530 --> 00:57:13.210
in a positive way.

00:57:13.210 --> 00:57:15.430
And then in came the parents.

00:57:15.430 --> 00:57:16.903
And the parents said, what?

00:57:18.570 --> 00:57:21.110
You're teaching physics
to my ninth grader.

00:57:21.110 --> 00:57:23.850
It's gonna destroy his mind

00:57:23.850 --> 00:57:26.650
or the hormone, you know,

00:57:26.650 --> 00:57:29.660
and parents had two
opposite points of view.

00:57:29.660 --> 00:57:32.700
One is you're watering down the physics

00:57:32.700 --> 00:57:35.240
by giving it in ninth grade,

00:57:35.240 --> 00:57:37.350
we should wait for the calculus.

00:57:37.350 --> 00:57:39.940
And the other was it's
too much for my children.

00:57:39.940 --> 00:57:44.140
Both sets of parents objected
for different reasons

00:57:44.140 --> 00:57:49.140
and the the school board

00:57:49.170 --> 00:57:51.140
that had been so progressive

00:57:51.140 --> 00:57:55.410
in San Diego got fired

00:57:55.410 --> 00:57:57.140
and they had to give up the program

00:57:57.140 --> 00:57:59.550
even though when you really looked at it,

00:57:59.550 --> 00:58:02.150
they were really making
very, very good progress.

00:58:02.150 --> 00:58:05.160
Kids were learning,
teachers were enthusiastic.

00:58:05.160 --> 00:58:07.440
- [Man] You said 9,000 signed up

00:58:07.440 --> 00:58:10.690
but I don't know whether that's
20% or 80% of the students?

00:58:10.690 --> 00:58:12.640
- It was all, the whole school,

00:58:12.640 --> 00:58:16.030
everybody registered
for ninth grade physics.

